The @NJDeptofHealth Commissioner reported on Wednesday that between December 15th, 2020, and April 23, 2021, 1,319 breakthrough #COVID19 cases were identified in NJ, which represents .06% of the 2.2 million individuals who were fully vaccinated at that time.

Of those 1,319 individuals, 505 had symptoms, 377 had no symptoms, and an additional 437 did not have this information available in their charts. 92 of these individuals were hospitalized - 30 for reasons due to #COVID19.
According to data from the @CDCgov, 72% of all New Jerseyans 12 or over have received their first shot of a #COVID19 vaccine.
There were 14 deaths, half of which were deemed to be related to #COVID19 and half not.

Although all six state mega sites will be closing over the next few months, #COVID19 vaccines will still be available throughout the state. There are currently 1,800 COVID-19 vaccination sites throughout the state of NJ.

Additionally, the @CDCgov released a report (https://t.co/Hlp1ABDBSr) this past week that suggests that efforts by state and local jurisdictions to rapidly increase vaccine coverage could further reduce #COVID19 cases & severe outcomes.
Although the vaccines aren’t perfect, the state believes that this analysis (https://t.co/OIr5rG4iMg) provides reassuring results that the #COVID19 vaccines are extremely effective.
As of this morning, 9,158,939 total #COVID19 vaccine doses have been administered in New Jersey and 4,539,821 New Jerseyans are now fully vaccinated.
As the number of vaccinated individuals increases, the state is in the process of transitioning to a community-based #COVID19 vaccination model and closing NJ’s vaccination mega sites.

It is reported that while breakthrough cases were seen in all vaccine-eligible age groups, hospitalizations & deaths were only seen in those over the age of 50, and those over the age of 80 accounted for almost half of all hospitalizations & half of deaths related to #COVID19.
The @NJDeptofHealth has been studying cases of when fully vaccinated individuals tested positive for #COVID19. These cases are known as breakthrough cases.
